                <head>35. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In a letter to Chairman <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName>,
                    February 22, 1961, President <persName corresp="#p_KJF1">Kennedy</persName>
                    expressed the hope that “it will be possible, before too long, for us to meet
                    personally for an informal exchange of views” and indicated that he had asked
                    Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_TLEJ1">Thompson</persName> to pursue the
                    question of a meeting. For text, see <ref target="frus1961-63v06#pg_5">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1961–1963, volume VI, pages
                        5</ref>–<ref target="frus1961-63v06#pg_7">7</ref>. <persName
                        corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName>ʼs reaction to <persName
                        corresp="#p_KJF1">Kennedy</persName>ʼs proposal is described in <ref
                        target="#d41">Documents 41</ref> and <ref target="#d42">42</ref>. In a May
                    12 letter to <persName corresp="#p_KJF1">Kennedy</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> accepted the U.S. proposal for a
                    meeting in Vienna on June 3-4 and reviewed some of the international problems
                    requiring solutions. For text, see <ref target="frus1961-63v06#pg_18">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1961–1963, volume VI, pages
                        18</ref>–<ref target="frus1961-63v06#pg_21">21</ref>.</p>
            </div>
